<br>
The reason there are terms implied into the marriage contract such as an equal division of property is that this is seen as the fairest &quot;default&quot; sharing after a relationship.  People now know that's what they're getting into.  If they don't want that, then they need to know what they are giving up and get advice and do a pre-nup.  Prior to the property sharing regime being put in place, one person tended to be left with everything as they were the ones who had the most access to the property and the information about it during the relationship.  You can still arrange a relationship in any financial fashion you want, you just have to make sure the person with less power in the couple (financially, informationally) is agreeing to that with their eyes open.<br>
<br>
Courts enforce contracts at the rest of our expense all the time, though in divorce, it's generally an interpretation of the terms of the dissolution being determined.  This was always ambiguous - &quot;what would the parties have reasonably expected to have happen?&quot; - well the parties expected to live happily ever after and never thought about it, and it turns out that the two parties often had wildly different opinions on what they thought would happen.  So in most cases, the state has put up a default mechanism that in the name of &quot;freedom to do what you want with your property&quot; doctrine you are free to opt out of with the informed consent of the other party to the contract. <br>
<br>
(One side note, on custody:  most divorces, I'd say a huge majority, are no-fault divorces, and the agreement to dissolve the marriage is by living separate and apart for a time period, and custody isn't a matter of breach of contract, but the court's inherent jurisdiction to determine what is in the best interests of the child.  Different states/countries/judges will give varying weight to things such as infidelity so custody is always a bit of a crap shoot.  Even a pre-nup deciding custody ahead of time is unlikely to hold up as the courts aren't likely to see children as property to be contracted for.)<br>
